3,27.95,18.63,20.31,24.35,27.59,25.67,21.55,29.99,29.35,23.96,28.16,24.5,21.77,26.21,25.76,31.36,25.75,23.93,22.29,21.44,19.85,20.71,19.59,22.26,17.8,18.34,20.03,14.61,13.7,13.91,14.82,13.09,17.2,16.69,15.66,12.85,12.19,13.35,13.45,14.01,14.5,12.78,18.21,13.0,12.92,12.3,12.37,16.6,14.8,22.38,15.37,19.11,16.27,14.1,15.87,18.07,16.56,15.27,26.92,21.77,30.57,18.22,18.36,19.83,16.4,20.38,16.6,14.71,16.29,18.6,17.28,16.59,14.08,16.75,18.0,19.55,23.51,25.78,18.02,17.82,21.51,18.41,16.73]}},"releases":{"fomc":"Jul 29","ecb":"Jul 23","jobs":"Aug 7","ismMfg":"Aug 3","ismServices":"Aug 5","claims":"Weekly (Thu)","cpi":"Aug 12 (est.)","ppi":"Aug 13 (est.)","retail":"Aug 17 (est.)","housing":"Aug 17 (est.)","existing":"Jul 21 (est.)","pce":"Jul 28 (est.)","gdp":"Jul 28 (est.)","umich":"Aug 14 (est.)","chinaPMI":"Jul 31 (est.)","daily":"Daily","gdpnowKey":"Updates ~weekly"},"commentary":{"source":"claude","generated":"2026-07-17","items":[{"tag":"Energy","text":"WTI and Brent both surged week-over-week \u2014 Brent jumped ~$5.93 to $81.62, the sharpest single-period move in recent months, driven by renewed Middle East supply disruptions around the Strait of Hormuz. Elevated energy costs are feeding directly into input cost inflation for leveraged credits with energy-exposed cost structures, and are a key watchpoint for covenant headroom in commodity-sensitive issuers. The Brent-WTI spread has widened modestly, signaling tighter global supply conditions that may sustain pressure on transport and logistics credits."},{"tag":"Inflation","text":"Headline CPI fell sharply to 3.46% from 4.17%, and core CPI moderated to 2.57% \u2014 a meaningful disinflationary move on the consumer side. However, PCE headline at 4.07% and core PCE at 3.41% remain significantly above the Fed's 2% target, and PPI at 5.51% signals that producer-level pressures have not fully flushed through. For special situations credits, the divergence between falling CPI and sticky PCE/PPI is a key fault line: borrowers with price-inelastic cost bases but limited pricing power face ongoing margin compression."},{"tag":"Policy/Rates","text":"The 10-year UST yield rose to 4.55% (+14bps) and the 2s10s curve steepened to +41bps \u2014 a continued bear steepening that raises refinancing costs for floating-rate and medium-duration issuers. The Fed Funds rate holds at 3.75% with no near-term cut catalyst given sticky PCE; retail sales and labor data suggest no imminent growth emergency to force the Fed's hand. Bear steepening specifically pressures the capital structures of issuers with bullet maturities in the 2027-2029 window, where all-in yields are re-pricing materially higher."},{"tag":"Credit Markets","text":"HY OAS compressed slightly to 271bps (from 272bps) while IG OAS widened modestly to 79bps (from 75bps) \u2014 a mild risk-on tone in high yield offset by a slight IG softening, consistent with a market still differentiating on quality. VIX declined to 16.73 from 18.41, indicating reduced near-term tail-risk pricing. At sub-300bps HY spreads, the market is offering little distress premium; special situations investors should focus on idiosyncratic credit events and sector-specific stress rather than broad beta."},{"tag":"Labor","text":"Initial claims fell to 208K (from 217K), maintaining a tight labor market tone despite the payrolls print slowing sharply to 57K in June from 129K prior \u2014 a significant deceleration that warrants watching. Average hourly earnings ticked up to 3.52%, meaning real wage growth is modestly positive given the CPI print, supporting consumer-facing credit. The payrolls deceleration is material for credits dependent on consumer spending durability and raises the question of whether services-sector hiring freezes (visible in ISM data through May) are now showing up in macro aggregates."},{"tag":"Growth/Consumer","text":"GDPNow has rebounded to 1.68% (from 1.24%) and official Q4 2025 GDP printed 2.1%, signaling the growth scare may be stabilizing, though the trajectory remains sub-trend. Retail sales rose only +0.2% m/m in June \u2014 a notable step-down from May's +1.0% \u2014 though the control group (GDP-feed) held at +0.5% for a sixth straight month, suggesting underlying demand is more resilient than the headline implies. UMich consumer sentiment at 44.8 (a multi-year low) and a flat savings rate of 3.0% create a precarious setup for consumer credits; low-income cohorts remain stressed by cumulative inflation even as high-income spending holds up."},{"tag":"Housing","text":"Mortgage rates rose to 6.55% (from 6.43%), adding further pressure to affordability. Existing home sales fell to 4.09M SAAR from 4.19M, consistent with rate-driven demand suppression, while housing starts surged to 1,427K from 1,199K \u2014 a bifurcation that may reflect builder confidence on new supply but does not resolve the affordability constraint. For credit investors, homebuilder and mortgage REIT capital structures face ongoing headwinds from affordability-constrained volume and higher carry costs, but a construction activity uptick may benefit building materials and labor-intensive service credits."}]},"extraSeries":{"ecb":{"value":"2.25%","delta":"Hiked +25bps at June 17 meeting (first hike since 2023); next decision July 23 with ~93% probability of hold","dir":"up"},"chinaPMI":{"value":"50.3","delta":"Up from 50.0 in May; beat consensus of 50.1; AI/high-tech exports driving expansion, domestic demand remains weak","dir":"up"},"ismServices":{"value":"54.0","delta":"Down from 54.5 in May; 24th consecutive month in expansion; employment sub-index jumped to 51.2 from 47.9","dir":"down"},"retailSales":{"value":"+0.2% m/m","delta":"Down from +1.0% in May; ex-gas +0.7%; control group +0.5% (6th straight gain); gas station drag from lower pump prices","dir":"down"},"existingHome":{"value":"4.09M","delta":"Down from 4.19M in May; mortgage rate headwinds at 6.55% continuing to suppress resale turnover","dir":"down"}},"themes":{"refiWall":"Bear steepening (2s10s at +41bps, 10Y at 4.55%) is materially raising all-in refinancing costs for issuers with 2027-2029 maturities; with HY spreads below 300bps and base rates elevated, total cost of capital for B/BB credits remains punishing, pressuring issuers to pursue amend-and-extend transactions or discounted liability management exercises rather than clean refinancings. The payrolls deceleration and sticky PCE suggest the Fed is unlikely to provide meaningful rate relief before many of these maturities come due.","tariffs":"Tariff uncertainty continues to distort supply chains \u2014 China PMI export orders rebounded to 50.1 in June partly on front-loading ahead of potential new restrictions, masking underlying demand weakness. ISM Services respondents cited aluminum and lumber cost increases directly attributable to tariffs alongside energy-driven commodity inflation, compounding margin pressure for credits in manufacturing and distribution sectors.","mideast":"The ECB hiked 25bps in June explicitly citing Middle East-driven energy inflation and Strait of Hormuz disruption risks, and markets are pricing a ~70% chance of another ECB hike in September \u2014 signaling the conflict's macro footprint has gone global. Brent's sharp $5.93 weekly surge to $81.62 suggests supply disruption fears remain acute; ISM Services respondents noted petroleum-linked price pressures are expected to persist for several more months, keeping energy-cost-of-service inflation elevated for credit issuers with significant fuel or logistics exposure."}}